________FREEDISK

FREEDISK is used to graphically display how much free
disk space you have.  It draws a bar chart on your
screen, where each bar represents one disk.  The bars
are scaled so that your largest disk exactly fills the
screen.

Each bar will have a lighter part on the left which
represents disk space in use, and a darker part on the
right which represents free disk space.  In addition,
FREEDISK makes a brief report on available disk space.

FREEDISK normally examines every disk, starting at
drive C: (usually the first fixed disk).  You can
change that by telling FREEDISK the letter of the
first drive to examine.  For example, to have the
report start with drive B: you would say:

    freedisk B:

FREEDISK normally examines every disk up to drive Z:
(the highest that is easily accessible under MS-DOS).
You can change that by giving FREEDISK both the first
drive to examine and the last drive to examine.  For
example, to make FREEDISK report on drives H: through
M: you would say:

    freedisk H: M:






SEA Tools                                       Page 44
     FREEDISK can be asked to return an error level if a
     given amount of free disk space is available.  The
     desired amount of space can be expressed in kilobytes,
     megabytes, or gigabytes.  For example, to determine if
     20 megabytes of free disk space is available, you
     would say:

         freedisk 20m

     "M" stands for "megabytes".  You could also use "k"
     for "kilobytes" or "g" for "gigabytes" (you can't ask
     for more than about 3 gigabytes, as numbers on a PC
     don't get any bigger).

     This can be combined with a range of drives.  For
     example, to find out if drive D: has at least 5
     megabytes of free space, you would say:

         freedisk D: D: 5m

     FREEDISK would exit with error level zero if drive D:
     has at least five megabytes of free space, or one if
     it doesn't.


     FREEDISK can also be asked to find the first disk with
     at least a given amount of free space.  Just add a
     question mark to the space.  For example, to find the
     first disk with at least 10 megabytes free, you would
     say:

         freedisk 10m?

     FREEDISK will exit with an error level equal to the
     number of the first disk that has that much free space
     (1 means drive A:, 2 means drive B:, and so on), or
     zero if no drive has that much room.

















