Shift locks:

There are four "shift locks" on the PC keyboard.
These are Caps Lock, Num Lock, Scroll Lock, and
Insert.  You can have FAKEY can control these as well
by adding a plus (to turn it on) or a minus (to turn
it off) to any of the following mnemonics:

    CAP    CAP       For Caps Lock
    NUM    NUM       For Num Lock
    SCR    SCR       For Scroll Lock
    INS    INS       For Insert

For example, you would tell FAKEY to turn Num Lock off
by giving the command:

    fakey num-

Or you could turn Caps Lock on by giving the command:

    fakey cap+

Many keyboards these days have status lights for Num
Lock, Caps Lock, and Scroll Lock.  If your keyboard
is one of them, then you might want to try:

    fakey num+ cap+ scr+ wait num- wait cap- wait scr-

which will give you a modest three-second light show.



Programmed pauses:

We've already mentioned that FAKEY can be told to wait
for some number of seconds.  There are a couple of
other things FAKEY can wait for as well.

FAKEY can be told to wait until some specific text is
printed on the screen.  This only applies to text that
is printed normally -- FAKEY doesn't see what a
program does if it writes to the screen directly.  In
general, if you can redirect the text to a file, then
you can also have FAKEY wait for it.










SEA Tools                                       Page 52
     You tell FAKEY to wait for text by enclosing the text
     in square brackets.  For example:

         fakey [What is your name?] "Kilgore Trout" CR

     This would tell FAKEY to wait until some program
     prints the message, "What is your name?", and to then
     respond with "Kilgore Trout".


     FAKEY can also wait for a change in "carrier detect"
     on COM1 or COM2.  COM1 and COM2 are the two serial
     ports on a PC, which are often used to enable a PC to
     send and receive data via telephone lines.  "Carrier
     detect" is a particular signal from a serial port that
     (usually) indicates whether or not your system is
     currently connected to another system by phone.
     "Carrier detect" is "true" if you are connected, and
     "false" if you are not.

     The four FAKEY mnemonics for waiting on carrier detect
     are:

         CD1+         CD1+   Wait for carrier detect to be true on COM1
         CD1-         CD1-   Wait for carrier detect to be false on COM1
         CD2+         CD2+   Wait for carrier detect to be true on COM2
         CD2-         CD2-   Wait for carrier detect to be false on COM2


     For an overly technical example, a sysop of a BBS
     could activate a thirty second watchdog in a door by
     putting this command in the batch file:

         fakey cd1- wait 30 boot

     She could then disable the watchdog when exiting the
     door by executing the command:

         fakey toss

     Or perhaps she'd like an alarm when the watchdog
     begins counting down thirty seconds:

         fakey cd1- beep wait 30 boot










