Yes, we know that lots of people have written MOVE
programs (often called MV instead of MOVE).  Ours is
different -- it's paranoid.

Almost all MOVE programs take advantage of a gimmick
in MS-DOS, whereby one can quickly shift a file from
one directory to another on the same disk.  The good
ones go even further.  They detect when the move would
be between different disks (where the MS-DOS gimmick
won't work) and do a copy.

But in certain circumstances (like on a network drive
on our office LAN) where the MS-DOS gimmick ought to
                               ____work, everything looks like it does work.  But it
doesn't.

So our own MOVE program gets paranoid.  It tries the
gimmick, and then it looks at the disk to see for
itself if the file really moved.  If the gimmick
didn't work, then it does a copy.

Using MOVE is simple.  The first argument is the name
of the file to move, and it may contain wildcards.
The second argument is the name of the directory to
move the file(s) to.  If you leave off the second
argument, then the files are moved to your current
directory.



