     ________     WIPEFREE

     At first glance, WIPEFREE sounds like a very stange
     utility.  It overwrites all of the unused clusters on
     a disk.  Why in the world would anyone want to do
     that?

     We're sure you've seen utilities around that will
     overwrite every byte of a file or every byte of a
     disk.  They're supposed to be for security.  The
     general idea is to destroy any data that was super-
     duper ultra top secret, so nobody can ever read it.

     But it isn't enough to just write over a file, and
     writing over a whole disk might be too much!  Wiping
     out a floppy makes sense, but what about a fixed disk?

     Let's suppose you were working on a supersecret
     letter.  When you finally get it done, you send it to
                                                ______     your printer and wipe out the file.  Is it really
     gone?  Well, if you've edited it more than once,
     almost certainly your editor has had multiple copies
     of it on disk at various times.  If you have a print
     spooler that buffers to disk, then there's yet another
     copy!  Even after you overwrite the file, if you ran
     OHMYGAWD you'd probably get it back five times over!

                   ______     So how do you really wipe it out?

     Enter WIPEFREE.  Just delete the file, and then have
                        ___     WIPEFREE overwrite all of the unused clusters on your
     disk.

     WIPEFREE needs at least one argument, which is the
     disk to wipe.  For example, to overwrite all of the
     free clusters on your D: disk, you would say:

         wipefree D:

     WIPEFREE can take a second argument, which is how many
     passes to make.  For example, if you wanted WIPEFREE
     to overwrite every free cluster on your D: disk five
     times, you would say:

         wipefree D: 5

     When it's making multiple passes WIPEFREE alternates
     between overwriting with all bits off, and overwriting
     with all bits on.





